{"sequence":57,"timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:25:06.919292421Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-68b23572","body":"Handle resumed `iterative_minimal` stages that have already durably emitted `implementer_loop_exited` without invoking the implementer again. `reconstruct_iterative_state_from_events` only rebuilds state from `ImplementerIterationCompleted` events (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:1162-1191`), and `execute_iterative_plan_and_implement_stage` unconditionally increments `completed_iterations` before re-checking stop conditions (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6234-6245`) even after the prior run has already journaled `ImplementerLoopExited` (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6376-6398`). If the process dies or stage commit/payload persistence fails after the loop exit event is written but before `stage_completed`, a resume performs one extra implementer invocation, can exceed `max_consecutive_implementer_rounds`, and may mutate an already-stable workspace.","dedup_key":"d6abbe364d89bd374291822ef6ab293293d5db32d49144a38f962b9acb1a9193","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260418021911","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":58,"timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:25:06.929101841Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-ffd697a2","body":"Add an exit-check at the top of the iterative loop in `execute_iterative_plan_and_implement_stage` (src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6234-6244). When `persisted_state` is restored on resume with `stable_count >= stable_rounds_required` or `completed_iterations >= max_rounds`, the loop currently runs an extra (wasted) iteration before exiting. This can happen when a run is interrupted between `run_snapshot_write.write_run_snapshot` (engine.rs:6367-6374, which persists the terminal `(completed_iterations, stable_count)` tuple) and the `implementer_loop_exited` event append (engine.rs:6376-6398). On resume, `reconstruct_iterative_state_from_events` observes the same terminal state from journal `ImplementerIterationCompleted` events, but the loop body at engine.rs:6244 unconditionally does `iteration += 1` and re-invokes the backend. Fix: before `iteration += 1`, call `advance_iterative_loop_state` (or equivalent predicate) using the loaded state and, if it already yields an exit reason, emit the `implementer_loop_exited` event and return without another backend invocation. Add a unit test covering the resume-with-terminal-state case (e.g., `stable_count == stable_rounds_required` in `persisted_state`).","dedup_key":"bd45de496f5e437a76b7a2f185cee7ce58cfd0fa86a90fc18a7bc21b50928c25","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"claude","model_id":"claude-opus-4-7-max","reviewer_id":"reviewer-2"}],"run_id":"run-20260418021911","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":59,"timestamp":"2026-04-18T04:25:06.938829148Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-3-fdb3f000","body":"Replace the silent `.max(1)` coercion on `max_consecutive_implementer_rounds` and `stable_rounds_required` in `execute_iterative_plan_and_implement_stage` (src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6216-6225) with explicit validation, or at minimum validate at config ingestion in `apply_to_document` / the config loader (src/contexts/workspace_governance/config.rs). Today a user-provided `0` for either setting is silently rewritten to `1`, which (a) hides user error, (b) interacts with the resume bug above (a persisted `stable_count=0` would exit on the first stable round instead of the default two), and (c) produces behavior that does not match what the user configured. Prefer: reject zero at config parse time with a clear `AppError` citing the config key and recommending a positive integer, OR keep the clamp but log a `DurableWarning` so the discrepancy is visible in the journal.","dedup_key":"fc14cbaf9a920d55b117650f3177f9a8443935937fd19e1a14e10b7a610120d9","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"claude","model_id":"claude-opus-4-7-max","reviewer_id":"reviewer-2"}],"run_id":"run-20260418021911","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
